{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519610"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:13:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.68,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70437"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70437"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressive dyspnoea. She has a medical history of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, persistent atrial fibrillation refractory to other antiarrhythmic medications, and recurrent urinary tract infections treated with cephalexin and amoxicillin. Her regular medications include amiodarone 200 mg daily for the past three years, apixaban, bisoprolol 5 mg daily, and furosemide 40 mg daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in moderate respiratory distress. Her pulse rate is 82/min and irregularly irregular, blood pressure 138/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Auscultation reveals dry crackles throughout her lung fields. Investigations reveal a normal chest X-ray. CT chest shows diffuse ground-glass opacities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apixaban","Bisoprolol","Amiodarone","Cephalexin","Furosemide"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has been on long-term \u003Cstrong\u003Eamiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E therapy for atrial fibrillation in the setting of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, where maintaining sinus rhythm is particularly important. This patient has developed amiodarone-induced pulmonary toxicity (APT), which typically presents with dyspnoea, dry crackles on examination, and diffuse ground-glass opacities on CT chest. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmiodarone is a class III antiarrhythmic drug with complex pharmacokinetics, including a very long half-life (up to 100 days) due to its lipophilic nature and tissue accumulation. It requires loading doses initially, followed by maintenance therapy. Amiodarone has numerous potential adverse effects due to its iodine content and tendency to accumulate in various tissues. Common side effects include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Pulmonary: interstitial pneumonitis, pulmonary fibrosis (occurs in 1-17% of patients)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Thyroid: both hyper- and hypothyroidism\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Liver: transaminitis, cirrhosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Skin: photosensitivity, blue-grey discoloration\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Eyes: corneal microdeposits\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Neurological: peripheral neuropathy, tremor\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of pulmonary toxicity increases with higher daily doses (\u0026gt;400 mg/day) and longer duration of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is essential for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation but does not cause pulmonary toxicity. While direct oral anticoagulants can rarely cause diffuse alveolar hemorrhage, this would typically present with hemoptysis and different radiological findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is commonly used for rate control in atrial fibrillation and management of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. While it can cause bronchospasm in susceptible patients, it does not cause the radiological changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECephalexin\u003C/strong\u003E is a first-generation cephalosporin antibiotic commonly used to treat urinary tract infections. It is not associated with pulmonary toxicity or interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E, a loop diuretic, is frequently used to manage fluid overload. However, it does not typically cause pulmonary toxicity or the CT findings seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of amiodarone pulmonary toxicity involves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Immediate discontinuation of amiodarone\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Consideration of systemic corticosteroids in severe cases\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Close monitoring due to the long half-life of amiodarone\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Alternative strategies for rhythm control\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5. Regular follow-up chest imaging to monitor resolution. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention involves baseline chest imaging, pulmonary function tests, and regular monitoring of thyroid and liver function during therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amiodarone is commonly used to maintain sinus rhythm in patients with atrial fibrillation who have failed or cannot tolerate other antiarrhythmic medications.","Amiodarone-induced pulmonary toxicity typically presents with progressive dyspnoea, dry crackles on examination, and diffuse ground-glass opacities on CT chest.","Risk of amiodarone pulmonary toxicity increases with higher doses and longer duration of therapy.","Regular monitoring of thyroid function, liver function, and chest imaging is essential in patients on long-term amiodarone therapy."],"references":["Florek JB, Girzadas D. Amiodarone. [Updated 2023 Feb 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482154/","Pannone L, D\u0027Angelo G, Gulletta S, Falasconi G, Brugliera L, Frontera A, Cianfanelli L, Baldetti L, Ossola P, Melillo F, De Blasi G, Malatino L, Landoni G, Margonato A, Della Bella P, Zacchetti D, Vergara P. Amiodarone in ventricular arrhythmias: still a valuable resource? Rev Cardiovasc Med. 2021 Dec 22;22(4):1383-1392. doi: 10.31083/j.rcm2204143. PMID: 34957778."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T12:09:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T12:10:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70437"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2"